               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>The <title xml:lang="ta">Vaḷḷiyammaipurāṇam</title> is a narrative telling the legend of <term xml:lang="ta">Vaḷḷi</term>, the consort of <term xml:lang="ta">Murukaṉ</term>. It appears to be an epitome of the <title xml:lang="ta">Kantapurāṇam</title> (Taylor 1845, p. 61).</p>
<p>The text is complete, with 67 <foreign xml:lang="ta">caṟukkam</foreign>s (Skt. <foreign xml:lang="sa">sarga</foreign>) and 1422 stanzas (U2, f115v6‒7).</p>
<p>Description based on the examination of the original manuscript (February 2020).</p>
<p>Dimensions assessed at the time of examination.</p>    
                  </summary>
                  
